eligious and political movements that encouraged emigration. By interweaving personal stories with statistical evidence Harper brings to life the reality behind the dramatic historical migration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBarnardo's Homes.  aCanadian government.  aEmpire Settlement Act.  aScottish emigration.  afarming communities.  afishing communities.  ahighlands.  aislands.  ajuvenile migrants.  alowland Scotland.  aoverseas settlement.  apersonal persuasion.  apoor-law children.  apopulation decline.  astate-aided colonization.  aunwilling exodus.  aurbanindustrial communities.1 aHarper, Marjory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611966740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119667423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119667/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles